Eu reconsiders leaving Pittsburgh for Penn

By Matt Groff
Asst. News Editor

University of Pittsburgh Medical Center
physician Dr. Freddie H. Fu, a national fig-
ure in sports medicine, has decided to “stay
home at Pitt” one month after announcing
his decision to leave the university to
become chair of orthopedic surgery at the
University of Pennsylvania.

Fu, who is the chief of the division of
sports medicine at UPMC, said hundreds of
cards and letters from friends and patients
at Pitt made him realize he should stay in
Pittsburgh.

“I am a logical person and a very hard

worker. Going to Penn seemed like the cor-
rect move for my profession,” Fu said. “But
I guess I really didn’t consider the emotion-
al side.”

Fu, who planned to leave Pitt in
September for the position at Penn, said he
had time to reflect on the move during a
recent vacation to Europe and Turkey.

“I realized how much Pittsburgh meant to
myself and my family,” he said. According
to Fu, when he retumed from his vacation,
there were many letters and “phone calls
everyday” from prominent people, friends
and patients from Pittsburgh.

According to Fu, Pittsburgh will remain
his home because of the people.

“No matter how much power, prestige or
compensation there is for any position,” Fu
said, “I would never be able to find this
kind of caring anywhere else. Staying here
is the right thing to do.”

Fu is the director of the Pitt’s Center for
Sports Medicine and is head physician of
the Pitt Athletic Department. He was instru-
mental in establishing the sports medicine
program which has flourished at Pitt.

In an interview last month, UPMC ortho-
pedic chair James I-Iemdon credited Fu with
“playing a large part” in moving Pitt to a
national leadership position in sports medi-
cine.

