By Jennifer McGinnis
Staff Writer

The smell of authentic food
and the sound of live bands
greeted those_who attended
Saturday’s Latin American and
Caribbean Folk Festival at Trees
Hall.

A wide variety of food from
Chile, Argentina, Peru, Jamaica
and other Latin American coun-
tries was available for students
to purchase.

A musical group composed of
violins, guitars and a vocalist
performed lively music while
the crowd of spectators clapped
along.

Recordings of different types
of Latin American and
Caribbean music were also
played.

The musicians also performed
traditional dances from different
countries, including a dance
which is popular at beaches on
the Venezuelan coast.

Many vendors brought goods
ranging from silver and beaded
jewelry to wool and hand-
crafts from Bolivia to the
festival. Scarves, woven purses
and belts were also available for

purchase.

A large star-shaped pinata
was featured as entertainment
for children who attended
the festival. Children also partic-
ipated in face and plate paint-
ing.

Along with food and festivity,
the festival hosted several politi-
cal and health-related groups.

The Department‘ of Health
sponsored free medical evalua-
tions to test participants for
blood pressure, cholesterol,
blood sugar, sickle cell and car-
diovascular risk.

They also made literature on
safe sex and drug abuse avail-
able in both English and
Spanish.

Political literature, brought by
the Pathfinder Bookstore, was
for sale.

“We carry a Cuban newspa-
per and The Militant which dis-
cusses different political move-
ments. We also have a lot of lit-

- erature on the women’s and

black struggles that are going
on in other countries,” said
John Cox of Pathfinder
Bookstore.

Representatives from the
Pittsburgh Cuba Coalition were
at the festival to offer literature
about the situation in Cuba and
explain the goals of the group
to festival goers.

“The Pittsburgh Cuba
Coalition is involved in a cam-
paign to get the U.S. to end
the economic embargo with
Cuba and to end travel restric-
tions that prevent ordinary citi-
zens from traveling to Cuba,”
said representative Sandi
Sherman.

“We are here to offer a differ-
ent point of view on Cuba,
and we believe that the U.S.
doesn’t have the right to eco-
nomically block and starve a
country into submission,”
Sherman added.

