Once again the breakthroughs of medical technology
are bringing another round of ethical dilemmas to be
debated and solved by both the medical and mass
community. Genetic testing is now able to predict who
is likely to develop breast, colon, ovarian and uterus
cancer, Huntington’s disease, Tay—Sachs disease and
cystic fibrosis to name just a few.

Although this new information could help lead to
cures for such diseases, dangers of the testing process
must also be considered.

A pioneer of genetic testing, Dr. Jorges Yunic told
Glamour magazine of how his initial concerns over
testing were brought to reality when a delegation from
the Chinese government arrived at his laboratory and
wanted his testing information on fetuses which
revealed small defects, such as cleft palates and IQs
that were slightly below average. It was essential the
only child couples had was as close to perfect as possi-
ble. Couples wouldn’t want to “waste” their only child
on an “imperfect” one; This exemplifies the dangers of

‘this new technology.

It is true that genetic testing would allow for more
preventative care, though many of the illnesses tested
for have no known cure. This leads one to question
how beneficial the information would be. Some say
they would rather be prepared financially and emotion-
ally for such a disease while others point out that one
may die in a car accident tomorrow and there would
be no benefit to knowing that today. This makes it
essential that testing is left up to the individual, and
that guidelines are in place to protect those who do
choose to be tested.

Without guidelines in place, those obtaining genetic

. testing could ‘feasibly be at risk of losing their health
} coverage, or possibly never be able to obtain it if tested
A at birth and found to be likely to acquire a serious dis-

ease. The implementation of universal health coverage
would help in preventing such discrimination, IF it is
stated clearly in the Clinton plan that testing can not be

. used to deny one coverage. .

More information must be gathered on how people
will respond to genetic-testing information. Just as
many clinics testing for AIDS make it mandatory that
those having the test receive both pre— and post—test
counseling, similar requirements should be made
mandatory for genetic testing. Never should such test-
ing be required or mandatory.

Testing should be optional only for those who have
been thoroughly informed of the procedure and ramifi-
cations involved.

Without guidelines in place, discrimination against
those showing the possibility of acquiring a disease is
almost guaranteed.

