The rock star success that he disdained and
fought to fend off eventually led to his demise.
In his final Rolling Stone interview with David
Fricke, Cobain said that he didn’t know how to
deal with his life. “If there were a Rock Star 101
course, I would have liked to take it,” he said.

But Cobain was more than a rock star because
of the effect he had on main-

Cobain was more than a grunge rocker

Cobain and Nirvana kicked in the door to the
mainstream world for all of the ensuing bands
that came later, from the laughable Pilots to the
packaged Nymphs. What became “grunge” start-
ed with Cobain and Nirvana. Pearl Jam frontrnan
Eddie Vedder said this past weekend, “I don’t
think that any of us would be here tonight if it
weren’t for Kurt Cobain.” Cobain not only pio-
neered the commercial movement, but he estab-
lisheda solid ground for the rest of Seattle to
follow.

Then the question that remains to be asked is
“Does ‘inﬂuence’ automatically translate into
‘genius?”’ In this case it does. Cobain was a
genius amongst a legion of wannabes, an unmis-
takable talent who left his mark on music in a
way that Sid Vicious did years before with the
Sex Pistols. They took punk to a level that
Cobain and Nirvana later eclipsed.

